{{Infobox monarch |name='''Abu Ali ibn Muhammad''' |title=[[Malik]] of the [[Ghurid dynasty]] |image= |caption= |reign= 1011-1035 |coronation= |predecessor=[[Muhammad ibn Suri]] |successor=[[Abbas ibn Shith]] |spouse = |issue= |royal house=[[Ghurid]] |father=[[Muhammad ibn Suri]] |mother= |birth_date= |birth_place=[[Ghor]] |death_date= 1035 |death_place= |place of burial= |religion=[[Sunni Islam]] }} '''Abu Ali ibn Muhammad''' ([[Persian language|Persian]]: ابو علی بن محمد) was the king of the [[Ghurid dynasty]]. He succeeded his father [[Muhammad ibn Suri]] in 1011, after the latter was deposed by [[Mahmud of Ghazni]], who then sent teachers to teach about [[Islam]] in [[Ghor]]. Abu Ali was one of those who converted to Islam during that period. After his conversion to Islam from [[Buddhism]],<ref name="Chandra">Medieval India Part 1 Satish Chandra Page 22</ref> he began constructing [[mosques]] and [[madrassas]]. In ca. 1035, Abu Ali was overthrown by his nephew [[Abbas ibn Shith]].<ref>''History of Civilizations of Central Asia'', C.E. Bosworth, M.S. Asimov, p. 185.</ref>
