{{for|the Scottish architect|John Chesser (architect)}}
'''John Chesser''' was an innkeeper and political figure in [[Upper Canada]]. He represented [[Prescott County, Ontario|Prescott]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of Upper Canada]] from 1835 to 1836 as a Reformer.

He was born in [[Lower Canada]]. His father and paternal grandfather were also named '''John Chesser'''. Chesser lived in [[Caledonia Township, Ontario|Caledonia Township]] and in [[L'Orignal, Ontario|L'Orignal]]. He served in the [[Prescott Volunteer Militia|Prescott militia]], reaching the rank of captain. In 1824, he was named [[coroner]] for the [[Ottawa District, Upper Canada|Ottawa District]]. Chesser was elected to the assembly in an 1835 by-election held after the death of [[Alexander Macdonell of Greenfield (politician)|Alexander Macdonell of Greenfield]].

