{{about|the David Attenborough documentary|the symphony by Gustav Mahler|Das Lied von der Erde}} {{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}} {{Infobox television |show_name = The Amber Time Machine |image = |caption = |aka = |genre = [[documentary film|Documentary]] |creator = |writer = [[David Attenborough]] |director = |creat_director = |developer = |presenter = |starring = |voices = |narrated = [[David Attenborough]] |theme_composer = |opentheme = |endtheme = |composer = |country = United Kingdom |language = English |num_seasons = |num_episodes = |list_episodes = <!--// Production-specific //--> |distributor = [[BBC Worldwide]] |executive_producer = |co_exec = |producer = |sup_producer = |asst_producer = |cons_producer = |co-producer = |editor = |story_editor = |location = |cinematography = |camera_setup = |runtime = <!--// Broadcast-specific //--> |channel = |picture_format = |audio_format = |first_run = |first_aired = 2004 |last_aired = <!--// Chronology //--> |preceded_by = ''[[Life on Air]]'' |followed_by = — |related = ''[[Attenborough in Paradise and Other Personal Voyages]]'' <!--// External links //--> |website = |prod_website = }} '''''The Amber Time Machine''''' is a BBC documentary written and presented by [[David Attenborough]]. It was first transmitted in 2004 and later became part of the ''[[Attenborough in Paradise and Other Personal Voyages]]'' collection of seven documentaries.
The documentary shows Attenborough searching for the identities of preserved creatures inside a piece of [[Baltic amber]] that was given to him by his adoptive sister when he was twelve years old. It then shows how a group of scientists can reconstruct an entire twenty million-year-old ecosystem through pieces of [[Dominican amber]]. Examples include a tadpole preserved in amber after falling from a [[Bromeliad]].
Attenborough then discusses the scientific feasibility of [[DNA]] being preserved in amber, and the science behind the 1993 hit techno-thriller ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]'', in which his elder brother [[Richard Attenborough]] starred as [[John Hammond (Jurassic Park)|John Hammond]]. Several attempts were tried, with DNA eventually being recovered from a [[weevil]] that was several million years older than [[Tyrannosaurus rex]]. Attenborough reasons that a few old, rare pieces of amber may contain DNA.
